[{"data":1,"prerenderedAt":135},["ShallowReactive",2],{"header-locale:\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F21\u002Fjs-weird-world-44-functional-programming-02\u002F":3,"page:\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F21\u002Fjs-weird-world-44-functional-programming-02\u002F":4,"alt:\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F21\u002Fjs-weird-world-44-functional-programming-02\u002F":3,"prev-next:\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F21\u002Fjs-weird-world-44-functional-programming-02\u002F":111,"related:\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F21\u002Fjs-weird-world-44-functional-programming-02\u002F":120},"\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F20190521\u002F399737087\u002F",{"id":5,"title":6,"abbrlink":7,"altUrl":3,"body":8,"category":93,"date":94,"description":95,"extension":96,"lang":97,"meta":98,"navigation":99,"path":100,"readingMinutes":101,"seo":102,"standalone":103,"stem":104,"tags":105,"tldr":108,"updated":94,"url":109,"__hash__":110},"content\u002Fen\u002FJsWeirdWorld\u002Fjs-weird-world-44-functional-programming-02.md","[JS Weird World] No.44 Functional Programming (Part 2)","1000300925",{"type":9,"value":10,"toc":85},"minimark",[11,16,20,24,33,36,40,47,50,53,60,67,74,78],[12,13,15],"h2",{"id":14},"intro","Intro",[17,18,19],"p",{},"By now we've seen how powerful functional programming can be. So this lesson is going to spend a bit of time on some resources and examples you can dig into next.",[12,21,23],{"id":22},"underscorejs","underscore.js",[17,25,26,32],{},[27,28,23],"a",{"href":29,"rel":30},"https:\u002F\u002Funderscorejs.org\u002F",[31],"nofollow"," is a pretty well-known JavaScript library that helps you work with arrays and objects.",[17,34,35],{},"The instructor suggests learning from open-source projects like this one — but before you take that on, you really need the concepts down first. So the goal here is to use these open-source codebases to deepen your understanding of functional programming.",[12,37,39],{"id":38},"lodash","Lodash",[17,41,42,46],{},[27,43,39],{"href":44,"rel":45},"https:\u002F\u002Flodash.com\u002F",[31]," is similar to underscore, but it runs faster.",[17,48,49],{},"That said, the instructor recommends going through underscore to see how it's written. Reading its source is a great way to really cement your grasp of functional programming.",[17,51,52],{},"Finally, here are a few resources I dug up:",[17,54,55],{},[27,56,59],{"href":57,"rel":58},"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bootcss.com\u002Fp\u002Funderscore\u002F",[31],"underscore.js (1.7.0) Chinese version",[17,61,62],{},[27,63,66],{"href":64,"rel":65},"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.html.cn\u002Fdoc\u002Funderscore\u002F",[31],"Underscore.js (1.9.1) Chinese version",[17,68,69],{},[27,70,73],{"href":71,"rel":72},"http:\u002F\u002Fblog.fens.me\u002Fnodejs-underscore\u002F",[31],"UnderscoreJS — a small but powerful toolkit",[12,75,77],{"id":76},"image-source","Image source",[17,79,80],{},[27,81,84],{"href":82,"rel":83},"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.udemy.com\u002Fjavascriptjs\u002F",[31],"JavaScript: Understanding the Weird Parts",{"title":86,"searchDepth":87,"depth":87,"links":88},"",2,[89,90,91,92],{"id":14,"depth":87,"text":15},{"id":22,"depth":87,"text":23},{"id":38,"depth":87,"text":39},{"id":76,"depth":87,"text":77},"JsWeirdWorld","2019-05-21 16:10:00","Once you've got the functional programming concepts down, where do you go next? This post points you at two classic JavaScript utility libraries — underscore.js and Lodash. The idea is to read the open-source code and work backwards from it, until the concepts turn into muscle memory.","md","en",{},true,"\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002Fjs-weird-world-44-functional-programming-02","1",{"title":6,"description":95},false,"en\u002FJsWeirdWorld\u002Fjs-weird-world-44-functional-programming-02",[106,107],"JavaScript","JavaScript 全攻略:克服JS奇怪的部分",null,"\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F21\u002Fjs-weird-world-44-functional-programming-02\u002F","A9TKC7TVpNN_CecymhB